At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange fell to the negative
After Tuesday morning’s fall, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange resumed with its fall the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market reaction to the result of the vote in the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan for the U.S. financial sector, is thus also noticeable in our country.
Stocks falling in Asia
Asian stock exchanges fell dramatically on Tuesday, even though indices managed to clear some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent as markets were closed in Shanghai.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange were losing more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“Hesitation about U.S. bailouts will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. legislators should soon resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the proposed financial system support, which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly K<0xC4><0x8D> 12 billion).
Legislators thus denied the call for support for President George Bush’s bill.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and major stock indices experienced the biggest fall in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having seen a fall of such magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it turned out that the proposal was not adopted, it was in a free fall.
Congress gives up: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in talks to adopt a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
In fact, before Congressmen can publish the final version of the law and put it to a vote, they must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, the chairman of the House's committee on banking and financial regulation, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan is expected to be voted on in the Senate a priori.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, there will be a "disappointment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a lot of progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the shape of the market stabilization package," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It is expected to repurchase the unsellable real estate assets from financial firms, which are causing significant losses to financial firms and threatening the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we are there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling stock markets.
According to the Democratic Senator did not escape Harry Reid, legislators are making sure that Congress reaches a final agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading starts on the Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect Monday's trades.
For now, however, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations are likely to remain stuck, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George W. Bush wanted, should be made available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the grant of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed progress in negotiations
Although the president may veto this decision, Congress, on the other hand, has the opportunity to put it in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the repurchase of bad real estate securities, whose value dropped, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George W. Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
Spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, says legislators have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, protecting contributors from losses, agreeing to decreases, and the time-axis plan.
The new law also provides for limiting such golden parachutes to the directors of the companies participating in the program and it establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for real estate owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new deposits in the case of mortgages that it is going to buy, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that it is not known what the mechanism and the price of the repurchase of the problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the loss-sharing between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, is, according to Marek, not as important as that.
"It is much more important that Congressmen agree, as early as this week, that they support this plan and that they will enshrine it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this moment," Marek stressed.
A struggle to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
There are plenty of reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end, expensive gramophone for the home to put on Maxim Turbulenc’s new album.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on vinyl record, and from a quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, at least you probably dream of such a grammofoon.
The same goes for music on the move, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have a hard time supporting headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobiles.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephone calls and sending SMS, it is able to read music and movies, record them, has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can roast meat and no television will take photographs, we are virtually witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two recharges.
And playing music is one of the most important energy streams.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count on that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you occasionally call from time to time, to be sure, get a second recharge for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of a recharge, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
As for the drives, you do not need, except (iPod), any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library themselves classified by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, focus on the battery life, memory capacity, sound quality and output type and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually every mobile device is capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
All manage to play MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have just this format.
It is one of the most common formats and aside from it, the vast majority of devices manage to play music in WMA format as well.
AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), on the other hand, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to purchase a musical motive.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and is limited, in most cases, to fast-made radio tubes.
The prices are also not the lowest.
Nevertheless, it is generally believed that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the internet, or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people still carry their motives.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best and best equipped phones, also equipped with an entry for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy control.
Really anyone manages to ensure the command of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even considering the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get away with even 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you’re one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and some Samsung).
These devices are provided with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of the control approaches that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series phones have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe...
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on Mobil.cz, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, has also confirmed this.
As a result of the European Commission's latest steps in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no longer room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with his own network is apparently not very lucky anymore (in fact, now he would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has resulted in a considerable price drop, to which later also the conventional operators had to react.
Yet even before parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
In addition, behind Mobilking there is the financial group Penta, which owns the U:fon in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for them to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators around the world profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good advertisement.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work in our homes as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czechia, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very conducive.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not, for quite a long time, concealed its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunication services, but also mobile.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not estimate that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators are also concerned with the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now.”
Vodafone instead focuses its attention on fulfilling requests for its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický says in this regard: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of fees and shared infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most contributions from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: at the same time as operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to understand themselves like thieves in a fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
Nowadays, the U:fon lends itself as an argument to not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems confusing.
However, it is not only the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
In the face of this problem, the latter took his typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," stated in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
A statement made in this way would not come as a surprise on the part of representatives of operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
However, pushing for an honest functioning of the market and for lower prices is apparently not part of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS's interests.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore none of them has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in its statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator quite logically has the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators visibly proceed in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in the negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility back to the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in communications, whereby the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted telecommunications law has not succeeded in extending the powers of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
This, the representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile phone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, there are companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price offers (and others).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you're talking about happened, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would consider and that could result in a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," said Martina Kemrová.
Nevertheless, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached the responsible mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned there may be thousands of customers.
An operator, however, does not oppose such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
Now, this is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
There is another question at <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable decrease in the price of services.
In practically all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were sometimes more, sometimes less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up creating a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are treating this issue like a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them in these cases.
But don't throw the handle after the ass.
If the backsliding information tells the truth and a virtual operator will soon appear with us, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will only be able to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
