Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
What a luck that the politician used the word 'relatively' and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This indeed happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains a loan of one billion from a consortium of German banks to protect himself from the turbulence of the markets.
A confidential person told Reuters on Monday that aid credits up to 35 billion euros were issued.
Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would thus be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which has since been impossible due to distrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank’s liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, while the equity rate had also weakened slightly from 1.6 percent to 1.45 percent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions fell to zero compared to the same period in the previous year, while profits from the allocation of fixed debt and securities and the termination of provisions in credit transactions fell by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only thanks to the significant profits from reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the Tax Procedures and Business Purchases Book for the Group companies that the earnings deficit of approximately 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially misspecified on industrial real estate loans, which later had been subsidiaryized to Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa had then become more engaged in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint private-state investor (PPP) projects and internationally diversified.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations which should have on the calculation of the group's gains and losses an essential material effect which still remains fairly blurred.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had been cut to two-thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor since the acquisition of Depfa.
It is stronger than other institutions that rely on interbank refinancing because it does not have any customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of loans between banks has again slowed considerably, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term refinancing means annually for a portion - about 50 billion euros - of all Depfa credits.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s need for financing is covered by medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of international financial markets that are currently largely out of step.
Other sources say that the refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
On the other hand, the chairman of the board of directors of HRE Georg Funke explained that the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group's market capacity is now secured.
The shareholders and creditors of the bank have only to hope for it.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest releases, still on the doorstep of insolvency Sunday late in the evening, this rescue for the least provisional will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debt at the top has barely moved, the prices of second-hand loans are declining.
The most affected are mainly the investment funds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and those that of course have a lifetime beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate bank previously seemed to be an alternative speculative investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the very institution that brought the crisis into the establishment by the acquisition of Depfa bank.
As long as issuing institutions, governments and less affected commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it can be assumed that there will be a timely reduction in delays.
Or it will happen what no one dares to hope right now - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that was approaching security has now become a mere grounded hope.
This should reserve sleepless nights first and foremost for long-term creditors to decide whether to part with their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have pulled a line on to make up a deferral of losses for the next few years on the next capital income tax of the stock gains automatically levied.
Sylvana and the Secrets of the Box in Bento
When 16-year-old Sylvana Hiltrop is due to show up for the first day at Tachibana High School, the girls start to laugh: German is so "kawaii"!
What does that mean?
Sylvana already knows this word thanks to the Mangas - in her new Log of Exchange, she speaks of Japan.
"The first day of class in Japan.
What I was excited about.
Already the way to go to school scared me.
I live on the outskirts of Tokyo towards Kawasaki and I take the train 40 minutes to Tachibana High School.
I had to find the way by myself, fortunately I didn’t get lost.
The beginning of the courses does not seem to be as strictly fixed as in our home in Lower Saxony.
Students appear one after the other from eight o’clock, until at nine o’clock minus twenty, a round of table begins with the teacher, the “home room”.
But before the class started, it was up to me to introduce myself.
I’m not at all like talking in front of people, especially in front of a class of 40 students.
As I didn’t have the school uniform yet, I put on an old skirt from my foster mother, as well as a shirt, blue socks and black leather shoes.
So in this outfit, I presented myself in front of the desk, and tried to pronounce everything correctly: 'Sayonara Wo she Sylvana...' - My name is Sylvana, I'm from Germany and my birthday is in a week.
At that time, I was very happy to have started learning the language two years ago.
The 31 girls in the class all did low masses, laughed and made signs, and I constantly heard the word "Kawaii".
I already knew him through my manga.
It belongs to the vocabulary essential to the survival of Japanese teens and means "cute, cabbage".
Then I quickly slipped into my place.
The girl next to me gave me a big ironic smile, she thought it was an honor that the correspondent should sit next to her.
The rest of the hour was quite quiet, but when the gong resonated, I was assaulted in the rules.
Everyone was talking to who was better, laughing and asking me a lot of questions - in this case it's quite difficult to understand English Japanese.
During the break, they all pulled out their Bento.
My host mother had also made me this kind of lunchbox - it's really something other than the miserable German snacks.
I had rice with aromatic herbs, small sausages, a cucumber and seaweed salad, fruit and some kind of meat surrounded by Tofu.
Most of the time, I have no idea what exactly I eat here in Japan.
Things have a weird appearance and a completely new taste.
What is certain is that everything is really good.
Well, except maybe the candied salted plums, brrrrr!
Bentos are not just lunches in Japanese schools.
Sometimes a girl offers a boy a Bento that she has prepared herself, and which is then prepared especially carefully - in the hope of being able to get a little better acquainted with the boy during the break.
I read this in my manga.
I'm curious if I could observe it here too.
"Why Japan in particular?" my friends asked me when I told them that I wanted to spend a year at school in Tokyo.
I always replied:
“Because it fascinates me, what?”
In the end, reading manga is what I have preferred for years.
