As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hard-to-work grounds because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it makes the dead, runs or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience to that of animals.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least, for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that human beings are even different from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence being related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, cannot be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses great problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of the conscious experience, but there is next to it another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine animal consciousness processes without regard to their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies of primate short-term memory, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, one focuses more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what happens then to the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its sequels, such as the body's reactions) grabs RAM.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute them to others than ourselves.
On the contrary, Antonio Damasio thinks that sensations from primitive activities are born in the areas of the body sensation of the Cortex and the brainstem, just like Jaak Pankseep, which however focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could quite participate in transversal sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I think it is indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and rats is likely to be felt as well in both cases: how could one yet verify whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but if he feels fear?
