The street is in the East Village and runs north of First Street—not to be confused with Second Street—between Bowery and Second Avenue.
About 30 feet wide for 120 long, it looks like a dusty driveway rather than an active artery.
. No signs indicate the street.
It is virtually impossible to find it on a standard atlas.
This street has admirers.
For example, there is Avalon Bay, the builder of the recent luxury buildings on First Street.
He would like to rebuild Extra Place, and create a smoother passage to stores and shops, which should open in new buildings.
Other admirers, including longtime neighbors, said they were charmed by this shortcut simply because it remains one of the last and oldest streets in the block.
But the Department of Preservation and Real Estate Development of the city that manages the street, has no interest in keeping it.
This month, at a meeting of neighborhood landlords committees, representatives of city agency and Avalon Bay drafted a proposal allowing the property builder to buy the street.
But the committee prefers that the street stays in the hands of the city, and has asked for a new proposal to be submitted next month, said Susan Stetzer, the local manager of the #3 Committee.
“There are few spaces left that belong to the city, and we would like the city to retain Extra Place,” she said.
“They might propose to rehabilitate and manage it, which Avalon might do, but we want to keep it public.”
Avalon Bay announced several months ago that it wanted to rebuild the small street and install seats there, some of which would be used by a café to which the builder will grant the space.
The proposal for this potential acquisition was made public at this month’s meeting.
Michele de Milly, the spokesman for Avalon Bay, said that while the company wants to exploit the street, this does not necessarily mean that it wants to own it.
"The main interest of Avalon Bay is to redesign this abandoned alley, and make it public," she said, noting that it was the city that suggested the sale.
Seth Donlin, a spokesperson for Real Estate Preservation, confirmed that the city wanted to sell the street, further stressing that the agency's mission was to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its more colorful neighbor, Bowery, Extra Place left a slight historical imprint.
Some believe that Extra Place bears this name since 1802, when the legacy of the large farm of Philip Minthorne's many children was divided, leaving this little piece of land, which has since remained abandoned.
The posterior entry of CBGB, a punk rock monument closed in 2006, reopened at Extra Place; the street is certainly more famous thanks to the cover photo of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia"
"This place was gorgeous," said Danny Fields, the Ramones manager, who took the photo in November 1976.
It was full of scraps, hails, barrels, posters, leaves and ropes."
Some residents, including bloggers who had already spoken about the East Village’s evolution to luxury, opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, saying that this humble little property should stay public.
Others have proclaimed Extra Place as a true rarity—a fragment virtually identical to the city that should be left in peace.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled "The Book of Contests: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look at a City in the Process of Extinction"), tells the history of the City and Extra Place, published in 1952 in The New Yorker.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac, dark by day and night, and bounded by the doors of a rusty iron warehouse and blinds, full of newspapers from the past week flying along the gutters."
With few exceptions, the street always looks the same.
A rat runs swiftly at the back of the alley, near a door that once led to the CBGB, and which has now become the headquarters of a chic clothing store.
Graffiti on the walls, an empty 22-ounce bottle of beer, rests next to newspapers that have just been thrown away.
A few passersby said they rarely think of Extra Place, and suggested its enhancement.
Mr. Field, on his side, said he thought some underestimated the appeal of the street in its current state.
“The best years of my life,” he said, “are taking place in dark, wet, and disgusting places.”
Bilingual Debate: Immersion in the English Language
In this part of the Education Supervision program, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a former California student, and former director of the education department at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "not as good as you thought. Why the middle class should be able to choose their school."
Attracting the favors of Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are an interesting example of this.
Obama’s campaign stresses that “African and Latino students are less likely to graduate than white students.”
To combat these differences, Mr. Obama’s education program particularly supports, among many other topics, “bilingual transitional education” for those who learn English.
However, the question that arises for Obama is whether his desire to achieve a bilingual education that advocates classroom instruction in languages other than English goes beyond his interest in eliminating differences.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The majority of students at this school are Hispanic, and low-income.
More than a third of the students, consisting of many newcomers, study English.
Among CM1 students, 100% passed the 2008 State Math Exam, expert level.
Similarly, almost 93% of students took the English-language-arts exam
This incredible success was achieved by another ingredient than that advanced by Mr. Obama.
Sixth Street relies on analysis, practice, a constant assessment of capacities and an exemplary attitude.
In addition, and here is an example that Mr. Obama could copy, reports Linda Mikels, principal of Sixth Street, this school instituted the instruction of the English language "full immersion".
The total immersion in English language focuses on the almost constant use of English in instruction.
Miss Mikels, contrary to bilingual education, told me, "We had tremendous success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, 12 months later, if you went without his class, you wouldn't have had any chance of identifying him."
“It works,” she observes, “it worked for us.”
Shouldn’t Mr. Obama take the example of the Sixth Street Prep and replicate it in other schools consisting mostly of Hispanic students learning English?
The excellent results of this school speak for themselves; but the policies on education within its party (the National Education Associations have long supported bilingual education) and its tremendous support for bilingual education obscure the prognosis of Mr. Obama’s response.
While he is in favour of the fact that immigrants learn English, Mr. Obama recently considered this issue insignificant, when he proclaimed that we must all stop arguing about the wording of English-language laws.
On the contrary, he said, "you have to make sure that your child speaks Spanish."
If Mr. Obama really wants to eliminate differences, then he should carefully consider the models of education that work, rather than disdain them or consider them insignificant.
