The Minister of the Interior wants that the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcohol, have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the start of the vehicle in a state of drunk, or if he does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last a year.
Its goal is the reintegration of the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State in charge of road safety, as well as the General Directorate of Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Automotive Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a state of drunk, take the car back.
The alcohol lock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced offences by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people each year.
This is due only to administrative penalties for two reasons: dealing with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means but, however, the reform carried out by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in school buses as it was done in France.
