Talking while sleeping
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a mild alteration of sleep that is called sleepiness.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, there are more than one who talks at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep impairments such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (piping in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or on the contrary with screams, weeping, long speeches...
In case sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a mild impairment, which is why there is no treatment unless it is related to another sleep impairment that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as sleepiness appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don’t be tempted to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because while sleeping, he is not conscious to be able to organize his thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate them during the night to learn their secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
