The interview - Blood became safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice as Héma-Québec became one of the world’s safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And most importantly, he regained the trust of the public who had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this tragedy and the grunt of the public, the Government of Canada initiated a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
As Justice Krever was delayed in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its business, just 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease were seen in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the one that holds the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when it is not known and a serious disease may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, blood was refused for those who had stayed more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
Now, a few years ago, it was proven without a doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the detection of the presence of the virus itself and not of antibodies to the virus directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowing it and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly lowered the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products annually, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues, before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide adequate supply.
“Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which accounts for an average of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Anyone who is 18 years of age or older and who meets the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country with malaria, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Because today’s life is so busy, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand cord blood samples per year.
We should start proposing for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed in not being able to access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program at all hospitals in Quebec.
