Free Opinion - The Orwellian Discourse by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the aim of launching a “transparent public debate”.
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of prosecution in defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will gag the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally occur through the exchange of ideas and not through the use of batons.
It was therefore sufficient for the mining industry to open its books, files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and letters of support for the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both demand a "public" debate while despising the opinions of the same public?
In the world of the Vice-President, it seems that this word refers only to the highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not as part of what many perceive as a gag suit (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice to the authors of Black Canada urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal discourse, the prosecution of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in its entirety, the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that displease the wealthy businesses of this world in a country like Canada, or else repeated prosecutions, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for academia, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of committed public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi, and Republican negotiating representative Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news just minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything was done in a way that protected the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing Wall Street crisis,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption in Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect of a further failure on investor mood.
The deadline agreed upon was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately involved in the negotiations, the two U.S. presidential candidates were rather supportive of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that we were forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with adding certain provisions to the agreement, including the one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of business leaders who have been rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no way to congratulate them.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on American television broadcasts.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something that we're all going to have to digest and with which we're going to be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsellable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (CAAPs) and leading to a freezing of liquidity and the debanking of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican constituents who had the first draft of the agreement overturned last week.
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of troubled companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it regain its placement.
The new plan provides for a first instalment of $250 billion, to which another $100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be approved by another congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain stakes in the rescued companies that will be worth dividends in the event of profit and that it will be able to resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for homes attached to real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and severance pay paid to managers of affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the House of Representatives vote today, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
In fact, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
"Obviously, Washington isn't listening to you," House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the benefit of the taxpayers.”
An animator of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman puts things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for €11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was refusing to acquire its competitor in the midst of shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"It's not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, we recover a right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that the times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank mistreated by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than $41 billion (US75.5 billion) in real estate loans.
Spain's Santander bank said yesterday it would buy the bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
