The Psychology of Overbiding: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be distanced in this type of competition, such as an eBay auction, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, a key element of which is the one-third overbidding, the set under the brainstem, called striatum, was moving heavily when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight to the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers pursued financial supervision analyses.
During these, three groups were overbidden against a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is actually that the emphasis was on victory in one group, while in the other was on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed at auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in the face of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading now to a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When Should We See a Doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that there are one hundred miles of patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are undergoing treatment. This is due to the fact that often patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and engendered diseases differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers are recommended to get vaccinated against A and B viruses anyway. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice develops, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most severe form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not known to have the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneezes the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does one who grows in God feel the least pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would already have contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article that researchers at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment in analyzing how much belief in God could influence human pain tolerance.
As part of this at least bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university participate.
Specifically, the experiment proceeds as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is fixed to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look sustainedly at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not much different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, received 20 electroshocks in four parts successively, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed one.
The Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like “safe,” like someone “who is taken care of” and they “calmed themselves, and peace has invaded them.”
When viewing the religious theme painting, they reported 12% less pain than when looking at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image that they react very positively to, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, the Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change and in many cases effectively change our personality,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if we showed the believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a better quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
You are what you disclose about yourself.
On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google says that it can be found in the bottom of people’s pockets just like the sky above their heads. It knows where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what their interests are.
This is not yet enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the influential people in society.
While skeptics are paralleling Orwell’s horror vision, they do not see the essentials of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times recently that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary for Google's founders to meet their initial goal that sounded like: "Let's collect all the information in the world in a system!".
According to the Google CEO, after ten years of global shifting work, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
To the question: what will be in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What job would be best for me?" However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, until the day they know enough about users.
It is not perfectly clear to all internet users that the words used during searches on the internet, the IP address of the computer that starts the search, and the pages viewed by interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the program Personalized Search launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they have searched for, what they have clicked on. Through this, long-term Recommendations, program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized responses, and will submit our previous preferences and products and services based on our statement.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my job is? ask users, who are worried about seeing Google’s information monopoly.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can provoke fear, and it is not remorse, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can provoke counter-reaction among internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the search terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases, they are passed on to a third party, and in this kind of legal case, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Probably the most striking example in recent times is the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights-minded Internet users were able to sigh a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm-up with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right to court against the FBI. According to the ruling, in the future, Google will still not be able to be obliged by any of the constitution’s points to disclose information about the FBI’s secret request, of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier, but ultimately it is not able to obtain the lists of private user searches, or the entire list of websites and keywords over the past two months.)
So Google’s judgment is quite contradictory: it is harassed by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and their private domain suffer from it when they start using Google services, so they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational corporations proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "wildlings" bringing together the passionate, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see in Google the next generation of big companies, the "connected corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, catalogued as an invader of the world because of Windows, and this even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and package of programs, continuously refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, in the face of the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very accurately the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, pulls right behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 is about nothing other than collaboration, than the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use communication channels at our disposal, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or to last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then he can link these to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also keep photos on recent Flicks, in which they appear more automatically on their blogs.
While we can take note of many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands at the sight of the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom his unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that has fired one of its employees, only for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about our private life, we can be sure of one thing about top management.
The person who lives an online life is made up of what he shows of himself, and this is how one can define the principle that hides behind the behavior of today's young people.
Someone wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to bypass Google’s monopoly, can do so (by starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who, deliberately, do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them, is not the least. The services of Google online, from the word processing to the image processing, to the reading of information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to huge server parks until this day and which do not assemble.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising domains threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the benefits introduced at an increasing rate cause serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other creators.
However, the critical observers find, alongside all of this, contradictions with disturbing effects: for example, the top management of the company refused, in its entirety, the protests of the employees, after it doubled the price of the company's kindergarten and after the company has found too expensive the daily multiple catering, taken at any time. All this seems derisory to the Chinese government that has already done the same thing.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced before health analysis only when they can be used. What's on, is that in the coming months and years they'll make the world move on new points. While some think that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines of Google takes such important dimensions that the company's other problems can soon be found in front of the court.
The fact that Google builds a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction authors.The famous novel by Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian halftones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way just through Google data.
