The intelligent automobile imitates the theft of the bumblebee
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, other than the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, taking place in Japan, buzzing bees gave the strategic idea to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini-robot, a bio-inspired BR23C self-driving system equipped with bee qualities, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval-shaped, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it weren't, the mini auto robot wouldn't be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," said Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collision is currently considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
In contrast to bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees have to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotational movement, the acceleration as well as the slowing as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lighter lithium polymer batteries with a larger energy concentrate, making their lifetime longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism only needs to process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don’t need a memory of gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing an instant avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will make its way into mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles in his path.
