Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to the month of August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased 1.1 percent from July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors increased by only a tiny 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with first, bag and belt manufacturing with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, then footwear production with 2.5 percent monthly increase.
Higher prices for plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices for the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and equipment manufacturing (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase, ranging from 0.2 percent to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which are a major factor in domestic industrial exploitation, prices rose 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of rising gas prices introduced by the authorities since July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, oil processing sector prices experienced the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the major food, beverage and tobacco sectors, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 percent of the previous year's prices.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the sectors initiating profit-on-investment that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material production sectors for further processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-initiating sectors, inflation was measured at 1.4 per cent.
Industrial export sales prices, in HUF, rose 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar. Compared to the month of August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and by 15.9 percent against the dollar.
