Mp3 player pointed with the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players, can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement released in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific report, let's read in the note, it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable music devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, risk permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use mobile music devices and full-volume mobile phones may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," Kuneva said.
“According to the scientific data,” continued Ue, “this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
In addition, we need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists-concludes the executive Ue- confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but concern is growing about hearing damage that could derive from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit this data by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods of time are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability after 5 years.
This concerns 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to about 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
