Elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
Yesterday’s New York Times confirmed this by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its moderate East Coast soul, favorable to federal institutions as well as the business community, and its new, conservative soul, hostile to “the Washingtons” and the world of finance, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, which was made to feel despotically with the vote I was talking to you about at the beginning.
However, what has just been cited is only one example of the changes, the great changes that the ongoing economic earthquake predicted or already lets go: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been breeding for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary revival, of the double category of state-sovereign, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that have, obviously, close relations with foreigners, but that, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalization seems really out of the question, or has little to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, is shared between the various interests and between the various national strategies, can not decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone is waiting for interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an affection for credit: when we are going through a difficult period, it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the still major importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite tied to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future will have to settle more and more with the rather little material things like water.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is, he who is unlucky to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shade.
And besides, something even deeper, in a sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership, feeds underground, either a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest in the "improvised electoral revolts" or else, in the changes of collective moods of the last time, from the conservative rise in Austria to Bavaria, to the rebellion of the Great Workers.
One has the impression that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, one would say, have ever more difficulty, which is not from today, to understand and therefore represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and agitates potentially in a disproportionate way.
In view of all this, speaking of a current “rebellion of the masses” on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But they say well, keeping your eyes wide open, that's not without reason.
