This is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to the public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work by voluntary developers, monitored by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is shown to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen, and the revised and less austere interface, to more important ones, such as the compatibility born for the Apple Mac OS X operating system, and the support for the new standard ODF format (Open Format)
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some functions specific to certain modules, such as the one that allows to reduce the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful, for example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into the graphical development module, retaining the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front, it is possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical graphic of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a text editor.
Collaboration between multiple people is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts over changes, in the preparation of texts, because each employee is assigned a color of comments for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some of OpenOffice’s features to the web (on the cloud, on the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they are expected to issue the final result.
The Italian version is downloadable at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and adds to the English version that had been on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual also available for the Linux operating system.
Upon request, the installation cd can be dispatched at home or at the workplace.
And if the theme of free can be a way to spread it in the homes, it is precisely in the business, that Open Office next attempts the great challenge, which can already count on various projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer a training, consultation and assistance service, ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which could also open up to business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for Word equivalent video writing; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint rival presentations; Dbase, such as the famous Access, is the program that allows you to work on databases; finally Drwa is the graphical module.
