Students are victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market is not experiencing a crisis
According to the latest survey of Sunia, the tenant union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support," explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of widespread increase has begun for them.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free, unregistered, no-rent-limit contracts, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of taxation are needed to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Bande Nere area), to an average value of 800 (Lamiate area, Udine, and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas near the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), one asks about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
One can only save if one moves away in the peripheral areas:300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a single one you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a major importance in the city economy.
Lastly, in cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent demanded from foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities touch the historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favor of multiplexes.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates well what is happening in the major urban centers of Italy, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of the marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the large multi-rooms, and the death of the consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems to us inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
“It is as if one of my friends disappears, someone we know, with whom we have shared a long way and so many emotions,” observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the potal grand prix of the jure of Cannes, and who was always telling the story.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have mostly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Roman Emilia is at the top with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the missed deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame that, ethically and morally, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would require between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas monorooms of historical centers and peripheries.
Among the normative provisions, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area, and will have special rates for parking lots and in some parking lots.
"This is an initiative I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna implementing other measures.
It is obvious, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important for me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had already thought about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much with shared emotions, I turn to the other side not to see the panels blackened by dust.
